Causes can be classified as eosinophilia affecting multiple organs and eosinophilia affecting a particular (single) organ:

  • Multiorgan involvement:
    • Allergies and asthma, DRESS [[General Pharmacology#Anticonvulsant hypersensitivity syndrome]]
    • Infections: helminths, ectoparasites like scabies, protozoans, fungi,
    • Neoplastic disorders
    • Immunologic disorders
      • Autoimmune - Sarcoidosis, IBD
  • Organs specific (or organ limited) involvement:
    • Dematitis - atopic and many others
    • Sinonasal and pulmonary -> allergic rhinitis, asthma, chronic rhinosinusitis
    • GI -> eosinophilic oesophagitis
      • Adults present with strictures and dysphagia with a history of allergies
      • liver transplant rejection
    • Renal - drug induced nephritis, transplant rejection

Consequences of eosinophilia

[!WARNING] Activated eosinophils can damage organs
by release of granule contents, lipid mediators and cytokines.
But this usually occurs when the absolute eosinophil count > 1500 cell / microLiter

Target organs : any organ can be involved by the most commonly involved are the

  • skin
  • airways
  • and GI tract

#2020GM-NOV/Q14

  • Burkholderia pseudomallei
  • facultative intracellular (facultative cos it can survive outside cells - in the environment as well)
  • Gram negative (negative - pink); Characteristic bipolar safety-pin appearance.
  • An environmental organism. (as opposed to zoonosis - it's a saprophyte)
  • Extensive antibiotic resistance
    • characteristically resistant to gentamicin
  • Ceftazidime works - but requires long course (2-4 weeks)
  • followed by months of coamoxiclav / cotrimoxazole.
    Exposure to soil and water.
    Risk factors for severe disease: (i.e patient who have comorbidities)
  • Diabetes - particularly common

Pneumonia is the commonest manifestation of legionella infection. Infection of other sites is rare.
Can cause mild to severe disease.

  • Associated hyponatremia
  • CRP > 100;
  • GI symptoms
    Commonest manifestation is upper respiratory tract infection.
    Most mycoplasma associated URTI and LRTI are mild and self limiting; They may not even need ABx. Pursuing a microbiological diagnosis usually isn't necessary as management won't change.

Q fever: Coxiella burnetti


Zoonosis; commonest reservoir is goats, cattle, cats.
Infective fluids come from anogenital systems : faeces, urine, birth products and milk.
Infection is by inhalation of aerosols.
Infection can cause:

  • mild flu like illness
  • Hepatitis
  • Pneumonia
    Chronic infection manifests as endocarditis

Enterococcal infection

#2020GM-NOV/Q14

  • Enterococci are commensals in the GI tract.
    • The two main human pathogens are enteroccus faecium and faecalis. Faecalis is more virulent but faecium can be resistant to vancomycin.
  • Clinically context: they are associated with nosocomial infections mostly of urinary tract: catheter assocaited UTI, cystitis, pyelonephritis but also infective indocarditis.
  • Treatment is difficult because they are resistant to many antibiotics.
    • They are resistant to penicillin and cephalosporins, macrolides, clindamycin, macrolides and TMP-SMX.
    • However, if sensitive, ampicillin and amoxicillin are the drugs of choice.
    • Vancomycin can be used if they are found to be sensitive.
    • Combination therapy with a cell wallactive agent (eg, ampicillin, vancomycin) and an aminoglycoside (eg, gentamicin, streptomycin) has long been regarded as the standard of care for E faecalis native valve endocarditis.

Streptococcus pneumoniae: Gram +ve coccus, alpha haemolytic.

Pathophysiology:

#2020GM-NOV/Q12
Coronary perfusion pressure is the gradient from end diastolic LV pressure to end diastolic aortic pressure. Source

Infarction spreads outwards from the subendocardial (note: not endocardial, sub-endocardial) region because

  • it receives the lowest flow from the coronaries
  • It's perfusion pressure is reduced by the high intramural pressures.
  • The contraction of myocardial fibers produces more resistance and blood displacement in the subendocardium than the subepicardium. Source

Illustrative point:
Both invasive and noninvasive studies have demonstrated increasing intramyocardial pressure from the epicardial to the endocardial surface of the ventricular wall.

Therefore, the zone of infarction spreads outwards.
Source

![INFO] However, the resting myocardial blood flow is GREATEST IN THE SUBENDOCARDIUM.

In LVH, there is preferential flow to the sub-epidardium rather than the subendocardium so that there is reversal of the normal subendocardial to subepicardial flow at rest.

Myocardial perfusion pressure decreases because of elevated LVEDP (secondary to decreased compliance)

Myocardial perfusion is thus compromised by the relative decline in myocardial capillary density and by a reduced diastolic transmyocardial (coronary) perfusion gradient due to elevated LV diastolic pressure - Source

Resting coronary flow is increased (?due to compensatory effect of autoregulatory mechanism) but because of this, coronary flow RESERVE is reduced.
AVA - aortic valve area.
Source
